  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Eulogy on a Portrait of Recorded Virtue
  author: Kwon U
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Humans possess the Way, yet those who embody it are rare—
    Only our Master Kil seems to approach such heights.

    The splendor of rank and the dread of authority
    he regarded as floating clouds,
    and departing with noble bearing, returned home.

    Ten acres of mulberry and elm,
    a thatched cottage with wooden gate,
    a small chamber filled with books and wisdom—
    there he sits in tall hat and flowing robes.

    When Zhou's virtue shone like heaven itself,
    it did not summon the one gathering bracken on the western mountain.
    When the Han dynasty rose renewed,
    it left undisturbed the sage in his humble sheep-wool cloak by the fishing shore.

    Though a thousand years have passed since those days,
    this heart, this principle remains true—
    unchanging and inviolable.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to "gathering bracken on the western mountain" alludes to the virtuous recluses of antiquity who refused office, exemplifying principled withdrawal from worldly affairs.
    - The "sage in sheep-wool cloak" refers to the legendary fisherman-philosopher, representing the ideal of honorable retirement from power.
    - This eulogy praises virtue that transcends temporal boundaries, suggesting that the spiritual integrity of the subject connects him to ancient exemplars of moral constancy.
